a’s best poets, alongside figures such as Lisa Robertson, Karen Solie, and Sina Queyras. Alessandro Porco’s introduction situates Burdick’s early work within the Toronto small press scene, focusing on her fugitive chapbooks, broadsides, and literary ephemera while highlighting her formative relationships with Victor Coleman and Stuart Ross. He traces her move from Toronto to Nova Scotia in the early 2000s and the impact of publishing from the social and spatial margins of Canadian literature. In her afterword, Burdick reflects on everyday life – as a poet and citizen, daughter and mother –in both the zombieland of downtown Toronto and the alien geography of Eastern Canada. She explores how the comparative speed, sound, and density of urban and rural spaces have shaped her literary imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian poetryy21st century. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aPoetry. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aPOETRY / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanadian surrealism.  aStuart Ross.  aelegy.  afeminist poetics.  amotherhood.  anature poetry.  apoetics of place.  asmall and micropress publishing.  athe analytic lyric.1 aPorco, Alessandro, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112382240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771123822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771123822/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles